6 Linear Regression and Its Cousins

This is a tidymodels implementation of the code in Chapter 6 of Applied Predictive Modeling by Max Kuhn and Kjell Johnson1. I have already implemented all code and models from this chapter using mainly the caret package in a separate notebook, APM_6.Rmd. In that notebook I used the solTrainXtrans data set as the training data. This data set has already had a transformation applied to it (Box-Cox). In this notebook I have used the full data set (un-transformed) and did the Box-Cox transformation and data splitting myself using the appropriate recipe.

Setup

# Load packages:
library(AppliedPredictiveModeling)
library(caret)
library(tidyverse)
library(tidymodels)
library(patchwork)

# Load my functions:
source("/home/brian/R/dir/Util/bh_functions.R")

# Options:
theme_set(theme_bw())
options(digits = 4)

Load and Split Data

The tidymodels process has its own functions for splitting data. Combine the pre-split training and test data from the solubility data into one data frame, then use the tidymodels functions to split the data:

# Load data:
data(solubility)

# Combine the data sets (update the name of the outcome vectors to y so that they are the same).
# Also give the data frame a generic name.
df1 <- rbind(
  cbind(y = solTrainY, solTrainX), # training data
  cbind(y = solTestY, solTestX) # test data
)

# Split data:
set.seed(1)
splits <- initial_split(df1) # default prop is 3/4
df_train <- training(splits)
df_test <- testing((splits))

# Create folds for 10-fold cross-validation:
folds <- vfold_cv(df_train, v = 10)

No missing data, and all variables are numeric:

6.1 Linear Regression

Training Data

Build a linear regression model and evaluate using cross-validation:

# Recipe:
rec1 <-
  recipe(y ~ ., data = df_train) %>% 
  step_center(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_scale(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_BoxCox(all_numeric(), -all_outcomes()) %>% 
  step_nzv(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_corr(all_predictors(), -all_outcomes(),
            threshold = 0.9) # same threshold as used in the APM text, but they say it might be a bit high

# Model:
lm_mod <-
  linear_reg() %>% 
  set_engine("lm")

# Workflow:
workflow1 <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(spec = lm_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(recipe = rec1)

# Use `tune::fit_resamples()` to combine the workflow and CV folds to fit the model on the training data:
## Read in cached results if available:
file1 <- "/home/brian/R/dir/APM/chapter6/models/lm_fit.RDS"
if (file.exists(file1)) {
  lm_fit <- readRDS(file1)
} else {
  lm_fit <- 
    workflow1 %>% 
    fit_resamples(folds)
  saveRDS(lm_fit, file1)
}

View metrics and store the training error:

collect_metrics(lm_fit)

rmse_train <- lm_fit %>% 
  collect_metrics() %>% 
  filter(.metric == "rmse") %>% 
  pluck("mean", 1)

Testing Data

Fit a model using all of the training data and apply it to the test data:

# Final fit:
lm_fit_final <- 
  workflow1 %>% 
  last_fit(splits)

rmse_test <- lm_fit_final %>% 
  collect_metrics() %>% 
  filter(.metric == "rmse") %>% 
  pluck(".estimate", 1)

Store the training and test RMSE values and parameters:

RMSE_TM <- tibble(
  framework = "tidymodels",
  engine = "lm",
  model = "Linear Regression",
  rmse_train = rmse_train,
  rmse_test = rmse_test,
  parameters = NA_character_)

Use the predictions to make diagnostic plots

Collect the predictions from the final fit and make diagnostic plots:

preds <- lm_fit_final %>% 
  collect_predictions() %>% 
  mutate(residual = y - .pred)

p1 <- ggplot(preds) +
  geom_point(aes(.pred, y),
             color = "steelblue", alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_abline(color = "indianred1", linetype = "dashed") +
  scale_x_continuous("Predicted",
                     breaks = seq(-10, 0, by = 2)) +
  scale_y_continuous("Observed",
                     breaks = seq(-10, 0, by = 2))

p2 <- ggplot(preds) +
  geom_point(aes(.pred, residual),
             color = "steelblue", alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0,
             color = "indianred1", linetype = "dashed") +
  scale_x_continuous("Predicted",
                     breaks = seq(-10, 0, by = 2)) +
  scale_y_continuous("Residual")

p1 + p2 + plot_annotation(title = "Diagnostic Plots (Linear Regression)")

The plots look similar to the results obtained using the caret workflow in APM_6.Rmd.

6.2 Partial Least Squares (PLS)

Training Data

Build a PLS model and train using cross-validation.

Use the same preprocessing recipe as used with linear regression.

# Model:
pls_mod <- 
  plsmod::pls(num_comp = tune(), predictor_prop = 1) %>% # 1 = use all predictors
  set_mode("regression") %>% 
  set_engine("mixOmics")

# Workflow:
workflow2 <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(spec = pls_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(recipe = rec1)

# Tuning grid:
pls_grid <- data.frame(num_comp = seq(1, 49, 2))

# Use `tune::tune_grid()` to combine the workflow and CV folds to fit the model on the training data:
## Read in cached results if available:
file1 <- "/home/brian/R/dir/APM/chapter6/models/pls_cv.RDS"
if (file.exists(file1)) {
  pls_cv <- readRDS(file1)
} else {
  pls_cv <- 
    workflow2 %>% 
    tune_grid(resamples = folds,
              grid = pls_grid, 
              control = control_grid(save_pred = TRUE),
              metrics = metric_set(rmse, rsq))
  saveRDS(pls_cv, file1)
}

Plot CV results:

pls_cv %>% 
  collect_metrics() %>% 
  filter(.metric == "rmse") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(num_comp, mean)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  labs(y = "RMSE (CV)", title = "PLS - RMSE CV profile")

The results are similar to the caret workflow and text (Fig 7.4, page 150).

Select the best model and store the training error:

pls_best <- pls_cv %>% 
  select_best("rmse")

# Store the training error:
rmse_train <- pls_cv %>% 
  show_best("rmse") %>% 
  pluck("mean", 1)

Testing Data

Fit a model using all of the training data and apply it to the test data:

# Finalize the workflow by updating it to use the best model:
final_wf <- 
  workflow2 %>% 
  finalize_workflow(pls_best)

# This extracts the parameters in the final model (this code is clunky, could probably be made simpler):
wf <- final_wf %>% workflows::pull_workflow_spec()
num_comp <- wf$args$num_comp[2] %>% as.character()
Subsetting quosures with `[` is deprecated as of rlang 0.4.0
Please use `quo_get_expr()` instead.
This warning is displayed once per session.
# Fit the final model using all of the training data and evaluate using the test data:
pls_fit_final <- 
  final_wf %>%
  last_fit(splits) 

# Store test error:
rmse_test <- pls_fit_final %>% 
  collect_metrics() %>% 
  filter(.metric == "rmse") %>% 
  pluck(".estimate")

Store the training and test RMSE values and parameters:

                 c(framework = "tidymodels",
                   engine = "mixOmics",
                   model = "PLS",
                   rmse_train = rmse_train,
                   rmse_test = rmse_test,
                   parameters = str_interp("num_comp: ${num_comp}")))

6.3 Penalized Models

Ridge Regression

Training Data

Build a ridge regression model and train using cross-validation.

# Recipe:
rec3.1 <-
  recipe(y ~ ., data = df_train) %>% 
  step_BoxCox(all_numeric(), -all_outcomes()) %>% 
  step_nzv(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_center(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_scale(all_predictors())

# Model:
# We will use tune() to find the `penalty` value. Setting `mixture` to 0 gives ridge regression.
rr_mod <-
  linear_reg(penalty = tune(), mixture = 0) %>% 
  set_mode("regression") %>% 
  set_engine("glmnet")

# Workflow:
workflow3.1 <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(spec = rr_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(recipe = rec3.1)

# Tuning grid:
rr_reg_grid <- tibble(penalty = 10^seq(-4, 0.5, length.out = 25))

# Use `tune::tune_grid()` to combine the workflow and CV folds to fit the model on the training data:
## Read in cached results if available:
file1 <- "/home/brian/R/dir/APM/chapter6/models/rr_cv.RDS"
if (file.exists(file1)) {
  rr_cv <- readRDS(file1)
} else {
  rr_cv <- 
    workflow3.1 %>% 
    tune_grid(resamples = folds,
              grid = rr_reg_grid,
              control = control_grid(save_pred = TRUE),
              metrics = metric_set(rmse, rsq))
  saveRDS(rr_cv, file1)
}

Plot CV results:

rr_cv %>% 
  collect_metrics() %>% 
  filter(.metric == "rmse") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(penalty, mean)) +
  geom_point(color = "indianred1") +
  geom_line() +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = mean - 2*std_err, ymax = mean + 2*std_err),
                  color = "indianred1") +
  labs(y = "RMSE (CV)", title = "Ridge Regression - RMSE CV profile")

The error is constant for low values of penalty before increasing for larger values.

Select the best model and store the training error:

rr_best <- rr_cv %>% 
  select_best("rmse")

# Store the training error:
rmse_train <- rr_cv %>% 
  show_best("rmse") %>% 
  pluck("mean", 1)

Testing Data

Fit a model using all of the training data and apply it to the test data:

# Finalize the workflow by updating it to use the best model:
final_wf <- 
  workflow3.1 %>% 
  finalize_workflow(rr_best)

# This extracts the parameters in the final model (this code is clunky, could probably be made simpler):

penalty <- wf$args$penalty[2] %>% as.character()

# Fit the final model using all of the training data and evaluate using the test data:
rr_fit_final <- 
  final_wf %>%
  last_fit(splits) 

# Store test error:
rmse_test <- rr_fit_final %>% 
  collect_metrics() %>% 
  filter(.metric == "rmse") %>% 
  pluck(".estimate")

Store the training and test RMSE values and parameters:

RMSE_TM <- rbind(RMSE_TM,
                 c(framework = "tidymodels",
                   engine = "glmnet",
                   model = "Ridge Regression",
                   rmse_train = rmse_train,
                   rmse_test = rmse_test,
                   parameters = str_interp("penalty: ${penalty}")))

Use the predictions to make diagnostic plots

Collect the predictions from the final fit and make diagnostic plots:

  collect_predictions() %>%

Elastic Net

Training Data

Build an elastic net model and train using cross-validation.

# Recipe:
rec3.3 <-
  recipe(y ~ ., data = df_train) %>% 
  step_BoxCox(all_numeric(), -all_outcomes()) %>% 
  step_nzv(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_center(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_scale(all_predictors())

# Model:
# We will use tune() to find the `penalty` and `mixture` values.
enet_mod <-
  linear_reg(penalty = tune(), mixture = tune()) %>% 
  set_mode("regression") %>% 
  set_engine("glmnet")

# Workflow:
workflow3.3 <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(spec = enet_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(recipe = rec3.3)

# Tuning grid:
enet_grid <- expand.grid(penalty = c(0, 0.01, .1), 
                         mixture = seq(0.05, 1, length = 20))

# Use `tune::tune_grid()` to combine the workflow and CV folds to fit the model on the training data:
## Read in cached results if available:
file1 <- "/home/brian/R/dir/APM/chapter6/models/enet_cv.RDS"
if (file.exists(file1)) {
  enet_cv <- readRDS(file1)
} else {
  enet_cv <- 
    workflow3.3 %>% 
    tune_grid(resamples = folds,
              grid = enet_grid,
              control = control_grid(save_pred = TRUE),
              metrics = metric_set(rmse, rsq))
  saveRDS(enet_cv, file1)
}

Plot CV results:

enet_cv %>% 
  collect_metrics() %>% 
  filter(.metric == "rmse") %>% 
  mutate(penalty = factor(penalty)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(mixture, mean, color = penalty)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  labs(x = "Proportion of Lasso Penalty (mixture)", y = "RMSE (CV)", color = "Amount of Regularization (penalty)",
       title = "Elastic Net - RMSE CV profile") +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

The error is relatively constant for the lower penalty values. For the largest penalty value (0.1), the error increases with increases lasso penalty.

Select the best model and store the training error:

enet_best <- enet_cv %>% 
  select_best("rmse")

# Store the training error:
rmse_train <- enet_cv %>% 
  show_best("rmse") %>% 
  pluck("mean", 1)
